commit_message:
Adds Initial Logging Support

Previously, logging was hard coded into the nova and neutron
containers. This patch creates two common params for logging:

DEBUG_LOGGING
VERBOSE_LOGGING

and sets default values of verbose=true and debug=false. This patch
implements logging for Nova and Neutron. Add'l OS service config
scripts and images will need to be updated to use the logging
params.

Change-Id: I03d48005d5b4789aa3c519879a20d963ef1cbaa3

There are some questions here.
* Could you document the steps to generate the codes. For example, for Magnum devs who are not in the domain of swagger, what is the steps for them to generate the same set of code as you did?
* Is that possible to make the generated files more explicitly. Hi All,

I have committed the modified code for the client. This is a running patch.

Here I have also committed the templates which I have modified to generate the running code.

1. The Kubernetes API swagger-spec at magnum/common/pythonk8sclient/templates/v1beta1.json.

2. The swagger-codegen template at magnum/common/pythonk8sclient/templates/python/

I will add a README describing how to generate the code.

To note, the code is still not pep8 compliant. To make it pep8 compliant, more work is needed. But for now it is running well :)

I think we can discuss in next IRC meeting, whether we would like this to live in magnum repo or a new project or the cores can give their suggestion here.'}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-04-02 08:31:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-02 08:35:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add tool for translation conversion

Add my hacky script to convert Docbook PO files to RST.

This applies varies conversions on the original files and send them
to the new location.

Change-Id: Id11845d9e3b42cd947ec259b9d7958598ec86a29

commit_message:
Add Neutron subnetpool API

Add Neutron subnetpool listing, creating, updating, showing and deleting
Client API.
neutron subnetpool-list
neutron subnetpool-create
neutron subnetpool-update
neutron subnetpool-show
neutron subnetpool-delete

Partially-Implements: blueprint subnet-allocation

commit_message:
proposal to add ZhiQiang Fan to Ceilometer core

i'd like to nominate ZhiQiang Fan to the Ceilometer core team.
he has been a leading reviewer in Ceilometer and consistently
gives insightful reviews. he also contributes patches and helps
triage bugs.

reviews:
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/reviewer:%22ZhiQiang+Fan%22+project:openstack/ceilometer,n,z

patches:
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/owner:%22ZhiQiang+Fan%22+project:openstack/ceilometer,n,z

Change-Id: I7039873996f8069c2af684e3f0446454f202bb53

commit_message:
Fixing the running of jobs without data sources

Data sources are now set to required=False.  We are also
checking for an empty string in the code that translates
empty values for consumption by the api.

Change-Id: Icc6979a22c991f5e453adb18a41cc7b636038ca7

commit_message:
Follow-up to "Add retry logic to _exec_ipmitool"

Follow-up to address final review comments and remove unnecessary
_time code that was originally only added to the review to mock
time which proved unreliable for testing.

Original change: I698a8ff1cb70d7758ed05e59b858d9e40708dd05

Change-Id: I109942cec4c84d376c568eba32a57cfb7553a34a

commit_message:
Open Liberty development

Bump pre-version in setup.cfg to formally open Liberty development.
Kilo release branch will be cut from the previous commit.

commit_message:
change source ordering in check-sanity

GRENADE_DIR is being export by grenade.sh, and scripts should trust
that value.

$GRENADE_DIR/functions pulls in devstack functions, and needs
$GRENADE_DIR/grenaderc to be sourced first.

Change-Id: I046435f4d28fbc5c81ed4651035902d867977bf2

commit_message:
reorder clean.sh to remove warnings

grenaderc now includes the devstack target needed for functions to be
sourced, so it must go first. This also removes warnings we've got
from the cinder cleanup by adding tls.

Change-Id: I1d5b8c4b85d0588a208840e26ffdbb4e166008df

commit_message:
Remove cluster wrapper from response body

Cue API has been updated to remove the outer wrapper from the
response body.  This change reflect that change for the python-
cueclient.

* existing tests have been updated accordingly.

Change-Id: I4925bf006661fb7e12ba2e9766b50361b56c4f84

commit_message:
Update tempest config for current master

* Removes some deprecated options
* Removes some options where we set the default
* Removes compute-admin options in favor of the corresponding
  options in the identity section.
* Moves oslo-concurrency options to their own section
* Removes orchestration/build_timeout where upstream build_timeout is
  1200 but we had set 900.

Change-Id: Ie966b96e86fa25b769a108cfaebf96b76c5a9f62
Implements: blueprint master-kilofication

commit_message:
Fix wrong command for _rescan_multipath

The _run_multipath command is wrong, it should be 'multipath -r'
not 'multipath - r'.

Change-Id: I2b642de057c11be71b4724c0c22f8bdc3ca86191
Closes-bug: 1438956

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/159022/
so that the API user doesn't have to get the SAML at all.
Instead this plugin could be enhanced to just accept a scoped token
for the IDP, could perform the samlization as well, and return the
unscoped token for the SP.
3) I'm a bit unclear about lxml usage as noted by TODOs in the code

commit_message:
Add Saml2KeystoneUnscoped for K2K federation

Implement the auth plugin noted for K2K federation. The existing
Saml2ScopedToken plugin works for getting a scoped token.

Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte Sousa <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I6fc99882a7733f138c305cf3b48bd34be6ed4e2c

commit_message:
Add tox bandit support for python-magnumclient

Add bandit support for python-magnumclient executed via tox.  The
idea is to gate on bandit once we work out the kinks.  In the short
term, we will have an experiemtal job that can be run manually.  After
that it will be added as a non-voting check job.  Finally it will be
set as a voting check/gate.

Change-Id: I14d037cf611ea6efa9f8271e6e120cd11b764dc4
Partially-Implements: blueprint gate-bandit

commit_message:
Run Gerrit unit tests

In the past we didn't run the unit tests because they were flaky.
We should give it another try since the build system now allows
excluding certain test groups from running.  I believ the slow
tests were the culprit so we exlude it from the test run.

Change-Id: Ib5af53e698635dc7feb6fa97cb88a4814080fd05

commit_message:
Don't pass boot_option: local for whole disk images

This fixes an issue where DIB installs a bootloader on top of the disk
image's bootloader. For now, hack boot_option to show as netboot for
whole disk images (from DIB's perspective), and fix it for real in
Liberty.

Change-Id: I5cc41932acd75cf5e9e5b626285331f97126932e
Closes-Bug: #1441556

commit_message:
Add user features for Vertica datastore

A specification for this change was submitted for review in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/151279/

Features added:

- Add support for optional users when creating a Vertica cluster
- Add support for root-enable for Vertica instances

Change-Id: I3f0e328acfba6636b447871b0b1055534dbd32b0
Implements: blueprint implement-vertica-cluster

commit_message:
Fix 'langpack' consistency issue

- We use inconsistent terms for languagepack in the CLI
- languagepack commands use 'lp' and 'languagepack'
- app commands use 'lp' and 'langpack'

fixing this inconsistency so both commands use
'lp' and 'languagepack'

Closes-bug: 1441881
Change-Id: I3583a947db4e33297355efb92c692f70a69fa66e

commit_message:
Only admin can create public glance images

With change to use the correct "service" role for service users,
they can no longer create public images.
For this recipe, need to use admin for public images.

Added a public flag to the lwrp such that other non-admin
accounts can create images.   Made a note in the client cookbook
patch that this support needs to be merged in there.

Change-Id: I99e2febfdbf6f4bab260d897216f4ae768cf3315
Related-Bug: #1436050
Closes-Bug: #1441292

commit_message:
Rbd update volume stats in wrong way

Cinder volume uses a RADOS pool to store volumes and
update storage stats periodically. However, rbd driver
reports the whole cluster stats but not the pool's. This
is wrong. The right way is to report the pool stats but
not the whole cluster.

Change-Id: Ie18324ebd8b85f7b63dc034ba20857ae9e470804
Closes-Bug: #1434441

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Correct a syntax error in some hosts: patterns

Exclusions have a bang preceding it, after the pattern separator.
Not `pattern1!:pattern2' but `pattern1:!pattern2'

Change-Id: I594ed52dbef9f6d6ed82ff5a440bc94670979a13
Partial-Bug: #1438118

commit_message:
Update glance_store dependency

Pick up a newer version of glance_store which
contains fixes for the Swift multi-tenant store.

(Needs some minor test changes.)

Change-Id: I14bb3c1fbc40ed2a81dc6990cfe59ae825733d1f

commit_message:
Include version identifier for V2 registry

Move the V2 registry from '/rpc' to '/v2/rpc'.

This patch was autogenerated with:

for file in `find . -name '*py' | xargs grep -l '/rpc' 2>/dev/null`; \
do sed -i 's#/rpc#/v2/rpc#g' $file; done

Change-Id: I7a243c4169fa458c8fb116025b2fddda54ad4f0c

commit_message:
Glance: Update yaml to use api and registry params

Tweak the Glance parameters to separate api/registry parameters as
appropriate. This allows, for example, setting different log file values
for the API and registry in a sensible way.

Here we update the relevant yaml files to use the new hierarchical
(glance.api.xxx/glance.registry.xxx) form, this has already been
done for the seed json.

Change-Id: Ic543b1e4c55568c914aa87ca2c172abc905b68db

commit_message:
Changes to get remaining cert functional tests working

These include:
* Returning an exception if full CMC or extensions are requested as
  these are not supported.
* Fixing the stored_key code to properly retrive the private key
* Updating the cert resources functional tests
* Modify code and tests to account for encoding issues with newlines
  in PEM formatted data.
* Added db changes to accomodate larger values in barbican-meta and
  CA meta for certs and CSRs.

Change-Id: Icf178b812047bf73f90e694acda0b2a9915ca1cf

commit_message:
Glance: Create glance.protocol param for http/https

When we are able to start Glance using SSL other services which access
Glance will need to be able to specify whether they are connecting to
a http or https service.

This is just a first step, other changes (endpoint registration etc)
will be required.

Change-Id: I330edcc7be897e3ecf47f14bbf8f6ea9531847c9

commit_message:
Use hexhyp instead of hexraw iPXE type

This patch is using hexhyp instead of hexraw for the type in the iPXE
script (boot.ipxe) since hexraw is not supported on older versions
of iPXE.

When creating a link between the configuration file and the node's mac
addresses, we make sure that we generate the 2 versions of it one using
the dash as a delimiter (hexhyp) and one without delimiter (hexraw)
for backwards compatibility.

Closes-Bug: #1441710
Change-Id: I19be3a04e7d53eeb45a67908e34884935dc84a91

commit_message:
Prevent failures when running as non-admin

In some cases a skip method was needed to check for non-admin. In other cases
there was already a try/except to handle on-admin but it needed to be changed
to use is_admin_available. NegativeAutoTest was changed to push creation of
an admin client to the point where the need has been established.

Also fixed some skip_checks methods to call super first.

Change-Id: Ie58135285a4c95c2eed9c0462c4e76af3ad5d97e

commit_message:
restructure upgrades into per project directories

This moves all the project specific upgrade code into project specific
directories. This forshadows how we might break out this code into
external plugins. It happens all at once to keep a working grenade
environment on both sides of this change.

Change-Id: If47395c796bdb0ae2b8fe65bfe4b4556a6487c7a

commit_message:
fix trueorfalse usage

A bunch of the trueorfalse usage was wrong, and thus could not be
overridden. Also, if tempest is attempted to upgrade when the smoke
tests haven't run, it doesn't actually work. So adjust that
conditional appropriately.

Change-Id: I847a8c2ca7cd044cf02e18321eba00b6cc55ebed

[{'created': '2015-04-06 14:56:38.000000000', 'message': "refactor to remove functions-common

This refactor's the grenade code to remove the copy/pasted
functions-common from devstack and instead use the functions from
TARGET_DEVSTACK. In order to accomplish this we need to refactor when
the devstack trees are pulled, so that we always pull both the base
and target devstack trees *extremely* early.

We also need to include a small number of functions (mostly related to
git) in grenade to be able to bootstrap these trees. This is done in
the inc/bootstrap tree.

There are some slightly unrelated function moves into inc/upgrade to
consolidate all the upgrade functions which were scattered through the
codebase for clarity. inc/* will be the contract library interfaces
out of grenade (mirroring devstack).

To do this grenaderc has to be split between variables which can be
set without devstack functions, and variables we compute later. These
later variables will be moved into project specific directories based
on the plugin plan.

Change-Id: I1a2d1a1fed7858c4f3b51a19be2d12cc2d260a24

commit_message:
refactor to remove functions-common

This refactor's the grenade code to remove the copy/pasted
functions-common from devstack and instead use the functions from
TARGET_DEVSTACK. In order to accomplish this we need to refactor when
the devstack trees are pulled, so that we always pull both the base
and target devstack trees *extremely* early.

We also need to include a small number of functions (mostly related to
git) in grenade to be able to bootstrap these trees. This is done in
the inc/bootstrap tree.

There are some slightly unrelated function moves into inc/upgrade to
consolidate all the upgrade functions which were scattered through the
codebase for clarity. inc/* will be the contract library interfaces
out of grenade (mirroring devstack).

To do this grenaderc has to be split between variables which can be
set without devstack functions, and variables we compute later. These
later variables will be moved into project specific directories based
on the plugin plan.

Change-Id: I1a2d1a1fed7858c4f3b51a19be2d12cc2d260a24

commit_message:
introduce UPGRADE_PROJECTS

Introduce variable that is a list of projects to upgrade, this becomes
a setting that can be overridden by out of tree projects.

commit_message:
make javelin work in a read-only environment

javelin by default was writing state into the grenade source tree,
though there is no reason why it should be doing that. This puts the
artifacts into well understood writable locations.

Change-Id: I784fc22893fe5335bef2072f1017b6ac259b830f

commit_message:
Catch DBDuplicateError in MySQL if primary key is binary

In Gnocchi we use binary primary keys, and one a duplicate entry is
inserted the error is not catched. This patches fixes that.

Change-Id: I488628df1a3b91d842eb9fa76bc1878f12d37acd
Closes-Bug: #1368297

IMO filtering and uploading solum log is not a good idea because we cannot guarantee the log file is stable when we upload it. Solum log accepts log lines continuously and keeps growing, we may upload tenant Z's logs to tenant A's container."}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2015-03-27 20:58:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

James,

We certainly have to ensure that filtering takes into account the tenancy of the log files.

About the solum.log being moving target -- that is a fair point. However, that can also be addressed in filtering by filtering only the log lines that belong to a particular run. Assembly id will be useful for this.

The main problem is for us to upload the deployer logs to a tenant's container, we need to write them to a local file. And the problem is the openstack oslo logger that we use ('LOG.debug()') will write a log file for entire system to the file specified using the 'log_dir' and 'log_file' configuration variables.

Probably what we want to do is to figure out a way to generate a local file per stage using the Oslo logger. I spent some time looking around how to do this, but did not find much documentation around it. May be our best bet is to not use Oslo logger but use standard Python Logger.

Let me know what you think.

If you find more information on how to make Oslo logger do this, that would be helpful too.

Dev"}, {'account_id': 6662, 'date': '2015-03-27 21:37:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I think we should implement a wrapper around LOG.XXX(), and use the wrapper to do logging wherever we need both solum.log and user log. 

We could keep an user log handler in user's context and use it to write out log lines, close the handler right before we upload."}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2015-03-30 18:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2015-03-30 18:46:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-30 19:31:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-20 12:58:45.000000000', 'message': 'Plumbing to upload deployer logs to swift

In order to generate deployer logs to a file, first
we need to enable solum-wide log. This is achieved by
setting following variables in /etc/solum/solum.conf

log_dir=/var/log/solum
log_file=solum.log
debug=true

Once these are enabled, Solum logs from all the services
(api, worker, conductor, deployer) will start getting
stored in a single file (/var/log/solum/solum.log)

In deployer, we are currently uploading this file to swift.
Later we can filter only deployer logs when uploadint to swift.

Change-Id: Iea69f61716e0d8e6a073355c6fee6d228318ada8
Closes-Bug: #1428181

commit_message:
Add 'ntp' helper with more strong time synchronizing methods

- all nodes are synchronized by groups:
  - in first group only Fuel admin node synchronized,
  - in second group all controllers are synchronized (with admin
        node or external ntp server)
  - in third group all other nodes are synchronized (with admin
        node or a controller)

- if any node is syncronized to admin node (/etc/ntp.conf), then
  options 'minpoll 3 maxpoll 5' added to 'server' in the config.

- decrease waiting for nailgun after revert to 30 sec

Change-Id: I7fd4de836f72a20ee2317114a2f6e810a0e18353
Closes-Bug: #1433484

commit_message:
Restrict editing of managed records to policy based ACL

* Added new context param (edit_managed_records)
* Added new HTTP Header (X-Designate-Edit-Managed-Records:True)
* Added new HTTP Query param (?edit_managed_records=True)
* Added policy check (edit_managed_records), defaulting to rule:admin

Change-Id: Ib68369fd7302384fd4fbd1396baa513265edb0a0
Closes-Bug: #1441283

commit_message:
Allow node interfaces update if it's in 'discover' or 'error' state

Node inferfaces update is allowed when node is in one of the following states:
'discover', 'error'. It's locked for other node states.
It's not locked on node creation, i.e. when node.nic_interfaces is empty yet.

Closes-Bug: #1425901
Closes-Bug: #1428776
Change-Id: Icc60c432296c28e89d71b1fd0dd864870553a467

commit_message:
Add TOSCA networking features

Add implementation for TOSCA networking features.
Imeplement following tosca nodes and relationships:
  - tosca.nodes.network.Network
  - tosca.nodes.network.Port
  - tosca.relationships.network.LinksTo
  - tosca.relationships.network.BindsTo

Partially-implements: blueprint tosca-networking
Change-Id: Ic97094cd661cd8d118ed092a981f6a7e3c25f857

commit_message:
devstack: Put ovs source in $DEST

At least on my system, ovs was being checked out into the devstack
directory instead of $DEST (or /opt/stack).  Another part of the code
assumed ovs would be in $DEST.  It had been working because I had it
in both places, but broke after I cleaned out $DEST.

Change-Id: I54d601b0622844e2cbe50f6dac64762035863739

commit_message:
Fix the localrc issue

1.Since the local.conf need to live on devstack directory
Refine the cat command to be obvious

2.Also fix one issue, as devstack would use localrc directly
if localrc file exists, but localrc not have enable_plugin
setting. This would cause devstack install without magnum enable.
So we use local.conf as the default configuration kick point to
make magnum can be installed with devstack

Closes-Bug: #1441977
Change-Id: Ib06cd38ed9744d42e664ff92d486c29e7932851f

Add support for configuration of Glance RBD store

This change adds the GlanceEnableRbdBackend param which, if enabled,
configures the Glance RBD store to use Ceph.

commit_message:
Do not remove /etc/apt/sources.list, just clear

We used to remove /etc/apt/sources.list, but the 'command-not-found'
tool requires this file and if it's absent prints the warning. In
order to avoid this irritating message, we're going to clear this
file, so everyone will be happy.

Change-Id: I452a0350f3f98794a9ccdc7a963cb4a0878b87c2
Closes-Bug: #1439670

- check-novaclient-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/77/167577/3/check/check-novaclient-dsvm-functional/96d42d9/ : SUCCESS in 17m 51s'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-04-02 00:40:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

"compute" isn't legacy... it's what the type is meant to be, whereas "computev21" is a temporary bastardization created by devstack and specific to devstack which should not get sucked back into the novaclient codebase. If you want to use a non-standard service type like "computev21", then I believe you can already do that without any of these changes... just specify --service-type. If you want to help here, remove DEFAULT_NOVA_SERVICE_TYPE_MAP and the code that tries to guess service_type based on the version... the caller is supposed to expect the service_type to be "compute" unless they specify otherwise.'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-04-02 00:53:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

To be clear, service_type we keep talking about maps to endpoint names in the keystone service catalog. It has nothing to do with nova api. By choosing endpoint name "compute," we are choosing the endpoint from the keystone service catalog named "compute." We are not in any way telling nova api what we want.

That is why I think we shouldn't be making up any non-standard service catalog endpoint names in novaclient. It is deployment specific. And Matthew is right, it can be controlled by --service-type option, that's what it's for. If your deployer has set up an endpoint in keystone service catalog called "computev21," you can completely call it by for example 'nova --service-type computev21 show myserver''}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-04-06 13:22:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-04-06 13:37:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I looked over the design etherpad. I really don't think we should even have an os-compute-api-type, which appears to be a cross between compute service type and compute api version. We already have --service-type for shell commands, but lack an env var for that. What we really need here is an OS_COMPUTE_SERVICE_TYPE env var, for those who want the default for their usage to be something other than "compute". And then the api version can be parsed to determine whether you're using a microversion or not (matching '\d\.[1-9]' would indicate a microversion) wherever we have code that needs to act differently for that.'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-04-09 14:11:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Adds os-compute-api-type flag

--os-compute-api-type == "legacy"(default value) means that v1.1 and v2 is
used(API microversions protocol is not turned on).Default nova service
type is "compute".

--os-compute-api-type == "microversions" means that API microversions
protocol should be used when talking to the Nova API side. Default nova
service type is changed to "computev21"(needed  to get the correct api
entry point from keystone).

Change-Id: I770e0ef6f5f56cc3a0dfe6295b4c8d147e20bdf3

commit_message:
Revert "Remove unused AlreadyAttachedClient"

The removal of AlreadyAtatchedClient exception from neutronclient
suddenly causes the failure of neutronclient icehouse job.
It is better to wait the removal of the exception until Icehouse EOL
(which will come soon).

This reverts commit 30b198edec988d7c969c1edd4a2754bd9c9c79f4.
Closes-Bug: #1441969

Change-Id: Ifa02a4ca39bc9c0fe9b65d5b0d66c588885cb12c

commit_message:
Work with pymongo 3.0

pymongo 3.0 renamed mongos_enum to read_pref_mode_from_name which
was causing the unit tests to fail.

Change-Id: Iaa7fd7221c2e6c865633ef342e6b83304a1de655
Closes-Bug: 1441393
(cherry picked from commit 7c3fe6acaef6fc283c383fb79f06e388df6e6926)

commit_message:
Fix changing keys during iteration in matchmaker heartbeat

When starting heartbeat in matchmaker-redis, keys may be changed
during iteration and a runtime exception is thrown as follows:

RuntimeError: dictionary changed size during iteration

Change-Id: I016a449674619294196055614c62c2856002291c
Closes-Bug: #1432966

commit_message:
Use nargs for parsing multilple values in fuel2

That allows to do more control on command line arguments
by configuring argparse instead of doing that manually.

Closes-bug: #1441130
Change-Id: Ia89bb3f2d164d977b52f7201748053314ae135f3

commit_message:
Create tripleo-common project under TripleO

tripleo-common will be a python library which
will contain code common for Tuskar UI and TripleO CLI.

Change-Id: I3bd0d5f9e337fc8d6c99cbf9379d0ac56b89e5df
Depends-On: I5ae63c2ca3a5253897848b1e52a4475ebbd6b178

commit_message:
Make screen sleep time configurable

the sleep 3 in screen_it was added to make devstack pass in the gate
with exceptionally slow test cloud nodes. In the gate we now bypass
the screen path entirely. However the sleep 3 remains and can add a
couple minutes delay into local development runs.

We're not sure yet how low this can safely be tuned, so step 1 is to
make it configurable, then get devstack team members to try various
options to see what works.

Conflicts:
	functions-common

Change-Id: I0e6476176fc8589efc4e40e78c2231f704d14e45
(cherry picked from commit 4b2b14c4b94bc13035b8f6f043ee81eb58004c6e)

commit_message:
Simple rate limiting of image creation

Prevent users from intentionally or mistakenly spamming the
database with new image entries at a high rate.

Two new parameters are added

* image_create_ratelimit_cap
* image_create_ratelimit_sec

The rate at which users can create images is restricted to
'image_create_ratelimit_cap' images every 'image_create_ratelimit_sec'
seconds.

If either value is '0' this feature is disabled (the default).

DocImpact
Change-Id: I5b24d1c949409499cfb527361ef891e1ab74081a
Closes-bug: 1401170

    cycles in the graph.

    in the catalog for specific astute.yaml configuration.

  export WORKSPACE=/tmp/fuel_noop_tests
  mkdir -p $WORKSPACE
  ./utils/jenkins/fuel_noop_tests.sh

It iterates over astsute.yaml files and runs rspec tests for puppet
tasks configured in the astute.yaml for the node.

    in the catalog for specific astute.yaml configuration.

In order to test just execute these commands:
  export WORKSPACE=/tmp/fuel_noop_tests
  mkdir -p $WORKSPACE
  ./utils/jenkins/fuel_noop_tests.sh

It iterates over astsute.yaml files and runs rspec tests for puppet
tasks configured in the astute.yaml for the node.

In order to run specific test and/or specific astute.yaml, you can
set appropriate env variables. For example:
  export NOOP_TEST="keystone/*"
  export NOOP_YAMLS="tests/noop/astute.yaml/novanet_flat.primary-controller.yaml"
  ./utils/jenkins/fuel_noop_tests.sh

If you also want to store puppet logs in case of errors, please set
PUPPET_LOGS_DIR env variable:

commit_message:
Modular noop tests

We can run noop tests via 'rake spec'. This will allow us to:

  - Make sure that catalog compiles and there are no dependency
    cycles in the graph.
  - Use RSpec tests to check that needed puppet resources present
    in the catalog for specific astute.yaml configuration.

In order to test just execute these commands:
  export WORKSPACE=/tmp/fuel_noop_tests
  mkdir -p $WORKSPACE
  ./utils/jenkins/fuel_noop_tests.sh

It iterates over astsute.yaml files and runs rspec tests for puppet
tasks configured in the astute.yaml for the node.

In order to run specific test and/or specific astute.yaml, you can
set appropriate env variables. For example:
  export NOOP_TEST="keystone/*"
  export NOOP_YAMLS="tests/noop/astute.yaml/novanet_flat.primary-controller.yaml"
  ./utils/jenkins/fuel_noop_tests.sh

If you also want to store puppet logs in case of errors, please set
PUPPET_LOGS_DIR env variable:
  export PUPPET_LOGS_DIR=/tmp/puppet_error_logs

If you want to store all the delcarated File and Package resources,
please set NOOP_SAVE_RESOURCES_DIR env variable:
  export NOOP_SAVE_RESOURCES_DIR=/tmp/puppet_resources

Related-bug: #1402738
Implement blueprint deployment-dryrun

Fuel CI temporarily disabled since this change does not affect
MOS deplyoment process, only CI itself.

Fuel-CI: disable

Change-Id: I38b23832d1e8701440aacb300256f513c466c762

subject: add ceilometermiddleware to requirements

I don't want to block this because I understand there are some issues being caused by this _not_ being here, but can someone explain why ceilometermiddleware needs to be in ceilometer's requirements? No code in ceilometer imports ceilometermiddleware and presumably that's what the requirements.txt means?

In the linked comment gordon says "ceilometer uses ceilometermiddleware to pull metrics via api" but that's not even true. ceilometermiddleware creates notifications that ceilometer can _choose_ to hear.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-04-09 12:51:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Do not detach/re-attach volumes in AWS Instance

Currently during resource suspend/resume/delete we manually
detach/re-attach volumes on AWS Instance resource.

This is not needed, as Nova already keeps volumes attached
to suspended instances, so the volume attachments are readily
available on resume, and automatically detaches volumes on
instance termination.

Besides, since AWS CFN has no support for stack/resource suspend/resume,
we do not have to keep compatibility with any CFN behavior
in this regard.

Change-Id: I38234d68467b5a4036e1a474a1e89d10686e1c3e
Related-Bug: #1393268

commit_message:
Make screen sleep time configurable

the sleep 3 in screen_it was added to make devstack pass in the gate
with exceptionally slow test cloud nodes. In the gate we now bypass
the screen path entirely. However the sleep 3 remains and can add a
couple minutes delay into local development runs.

We're not sure yet how low this can safely be tuned, so step 1 is to
make it configurable, then get devstack team members to try various
options to see what works.

Change-Id: I0e6476176fc8589efc4e40e78c2231f704d14e45

commit_message:
Validate tag name when filtering for images

Right now all invalid tags are skipped when filtering for image list. We
should change this behaviour to raise an exception when invalid tag
value is provided.

Additionally remove misplaced `pass` from one of the tests.

Closes-Bug: 1433962
Change-Id: If5148608a70ee019697ea2dcb84e19a53222d596

commit_message:
Fix the bug redis do not delete the expired keys

When using redis as zmq backend,
the keys in redis maybe like follows:

 "service"
 "service.host1"
 "service.host1.host1"
 "service.host2"
 "service.host2.host2"
 "service.host3"
 "service.host3.host3"

If we stopped the service on host1, the key named
service.host1 and service.host1.host1 shoule be
delete. As the result, the topicexchange message
would not sent to host1. But the fact is
service.host1 still exsit, and topicexchange
message may still sent to host1.

To resolve this problem , change the comparison of
ttl function from -1 to -2 according to
http://redis.io/commands/ttl

Change-Id: I5c0af97019fffed6e949eb58d7d60c85f5b08ea1
Closes-Bug:#1417464

Remove unneccessary noop jobs from zuul/layout.yaml

noop is only needed if there's no other job for the check or gate queue.
Remove it from:
* gantt: python-jobs includes gate.
* dib-utils: check-requirements includes check and gate.

Change-Id: I7f0ca96605dbc1bbaf9beb3c3c4dc7780c2a5006

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Sets *DataRoot paths for instances

Sets the path for the instance's ConfigurationDataRoot,
LogDataRoot, SnapshotDataRoot, SuspendDataRoot and
SwapFileDataRoot for vmutilsv2 instances and
ExternalDataRoot and SnapshotDataRoot for vmutils
to the instance's location.

Closes-Bug: #1430239

Change-Id: I3c9e2dece00df06cafdcd164ece6269337feda71

At the moment we use 1090 upstream packages. 544 of these are not included in the official Ubuntu ISO.

110 of these packages are not in the `main' section (and therefore are not included into the ISO). This list includes (but not limited to) qemu, zabbix, libapache2-mod-fastcgi, libguestfs (also known as guestmount), mongodb, monit, novnc, many python and ruby libraries used by OpenStack and Fuel.

Another 434 packages missing from the Ubuntu ISO are security updates for things like Linux kernel, python, apache, gnutls, bash (remember that wonderful shell shock vulnerability?), libc, dbus, puppet, corosync, libapache2-mod-wsgi, and many shared libraries

Therefore I think using Ubuntu ISO as a source of the upstream packages is a totally wrong approach."}, {'account_id': 10474, 'date': '2015-02-04 15:20:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-04 15:23:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: Verified+1

RPM packages versioning scheme in 6.1 will not change, so we're postponing corresponding changes until the 7.0+ version of this spec."}, {'account_id': 8786, 'date': '2015-04-06 13:07:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 55: Code-Review-1

I will post it again here so that you do not ignore it.

1. As we already discussed with Sergii ability to build packages locally will be kept for FUEL/MOS packages in order to make it possible for the developers to upload and test their code. This package building will be eventually based on Docker-based system which OSCI team is working on. It will use docker and corresponding package building systems inside docker containers. But release/nightly ISOs MUST be built from packages generated on code merge events.
2. For which reason FUEL packages should be built from specific MOS repository? What is the rationale behind that? These specs are very tiny and should be almost identical for FUEL or MOS FUEL (when there will be any diffference between MOS FUEL and COMMUNITY FUEL). We can easily add mos suffix to it, but there is no need to maintain separate gerrit repo. 
3. For FUEL packages versioning we already discussed how we are going to version FUEL packages and I think there was lazy consensus on it.'}, {'account_id': 10474, 'date': '2015-04-06 14:06:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 55:

commit_message:
Adding some middleware components for Swift

For now many middleware components are not added to the Swift
WSGI servers. Probably, some users will want to use them for
their needs. This is the list of middleware components that
were added to the Swift WSGI servers:
1. crossdomain
2. bulk
3. tempurl
4. formpost
5. staticweb
6. container-quotas
7. account-quotas
8. slo

Change-Id: I19aedf6cd39a3769d3c2d975786892d9b56e7d83
Closes-Bug: #1430765

[{'created': '2015-03-26 19:35:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add retry logic to _exec_ipmitool

When using bridged IPMI buses, the possibility exists for the BMC
to return messages indicating that it is too busy to service the
request at that moment.  This results in ipmitool returning an
error to the user instead of retrying the the operation.

As a result of the error being returned, the current operation
being attempted by ironic is failed and is never retried as the
present retry configuration is purely a pass-through to ipmitool.

Added logic to allow for the identification of errors returned by
ipmitool that can be retried coupled with logic to retry the failed
operation until the configured retry window has passed.

commit_message:
Add retry logic to _exec_ipmitool

When using bridged IPMI buses, the possibility exists for the BMC
to return messages indicating that it is too busy to service the
request at that moment.  This results in ipmitool returning an
error to the user instead of retrying the operation.

As a result of the error being returned, the current operation
being attempted by ironic is failed and is never retried as the
present retry configuration is purely a pass-through to ipmitool.

Added logic to allow for the identification of errors returned by
ipmitool that can be retried coupled with logic to retry the failed
operation until the configured retry window has passed.

Included three tests which are geared to exercise the retry logic
and ensure that the retry logic works as expected, including that
the retry operations are only performed a specific number of times
based on the conditions.

Updated one of the pre-existing tests that tested _exec_ipmitool
act of returning an exception to ensure that the retry logic is
executed only once.

Change-Id: I698a8ff1cb70d7758ed05e59b858d9e40708dd05
Closes-Bug: 1431929

commit_message:
Adds a note about NetworkManager service in VBox guide

NetworkManager may cause problems for clients using
Fedora/Red Hat Enterprise Linux (CentOS?) and who try MOS in
VirtualBox.

Related-Bug: 1396126

Change-Id: Ibe434e0d4fd1632c5eb9d16134ac41d2d289fd71

commit_message:
Added test for disk space check

Reasons:
    - A service engineer should prevent cases of space outage on nodes
Changes:
    - Added test for checking up free space on controller and compute
      nodes

Change-Id: I1aa1703b3182d5bff816e1858fd62ec8e753339b
Implements: blueprint disk-space-check

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-30 12:17:16.000000000', 'message': 'Creating metadef object without any properties

Creating a metadef object without any properties associated with it
raises an Internal Server Error. It is easily reproducible by running
following glanceclient command:

glance --os-image-api-version 2 md-object-create --name obj_name
--schema '{"description": "some desc"}' OS::Software::DBMS

The metadef object itself is created successfully, but the notification
is not fired and the response has code 500. Proposed patch fixes it by
making sure that notification system won't iterate over None value.

Change-Id: I591801d80d9cb2738dc3d27d7719fcc53a3d0645
Closes-Bug: 1438154
'}]
commit_message:
Creating metadef object without any properties

Creating a metadef object without any properties associated with it
raises an Internal Server Error. It is easily reproducible by running
following glanceclient command:

glance --os-image-api-version 2 md-object-create --name obj_name
--schema '{"description": "some desc"}' OS::Software::DBMS

The metadef object itself is created successfully, but the notification
is not fired and the response has code 500. Proposed patch fixes it by
making sure that notification system won't iterate over None value.

Change-Id: I591801d80d9cb2738dc3d27d7719fcc53a3d0645
Closes-Bug: 1438154

  ActionExecution is not bound to a Session; deferred
  load operation of attribute 'output' cannot proceed".

commit_message:
Fix rabbit OCF status check for reset_mnesia

In some conditions rabbit RA is unable to cleanup
mnesia because of the "reverse logic" bug in ocf
script, which is:

* It tries to check the status and rabbit is running
there
* But because of the reverse logic bug it didn't try
to kill rabbit
* That leads to "mnesia_unexpectedly_running" error.

Closes-Bug: #1441226

Change-Id: I2c71935148ad842ee5682112af6fb4e06bcc794f

commit_message:
Fix rabbit OCF status check for reset_mnesia

In some conditions rabbit RA is unable to cleanup
mnesia because of the "reverse logic" bug in ocf
script, which is:

* It tries to check the status and rabbit is running
there
* But because of the reverse logic bug it didn't try
to kill rabbit
* That leads to "mnesia_unexpectedly_running" error.

Closes-Bug: #1441226

Change-Id: I2c71935148ad842ee5682112af6fb4e06bcc794f

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-16 10:34:29.000000000', 'message': "fix concurrency issue with file lock

With file driver, when two threads acquire the lock, when the first one
releases it, the second get a 'ValueError: I/O operation on closed file'
because the first have closed the file after releasing the lock.

Now, the file is open when the lock object is created and we let the GC
to close it when we don't need it anymore

Change-Id: Ic990a79c9baebe534409c1a433e21f4a2f9a7d6a
"}, {'created': '2015-03-17 08:03:20.000000000', 'message': "fix lock concurrency issues with certain drivers

This change adds a test to ensure that lock acquired from different
thread works as expected. And fixes drivers when they won't.

With file driver, when two threads acquire the lock, when the first one
releases it, the second get a 'ValueError: I/O operation on closed file'
because the first have closed the file after releasing the lock.
Now, the file is open when the lock object is created and we let the GC

commit_message:
fix lock concurrency issues with certain drivers

This change adds a test to ensure that lock acquired from different
threads/processes work as expected. And fixes drivers when they won't.

With file driver, when two threads acquire the lock, when the first one
releases it, the second get a 'ValueError: I/O operation on closed file'
because the first have closed the file after releasing the lock.
Now, the file is open when the lock object is created and we let the GC
to close it when we don't need it anymore

With mysql, postgres, kazoo driver, multiple acquire inside the same
backend session, doesn't work like a exclusive lock, so we track the
status locally when we get the lock inside a process.

Change-Id: Ic990a79c9baebe534409c1a433e21f4a2f9a7d6a

[{'created': '2015-04-06 23:21:08.000000000', 'message': "Add simple ARP spoofing protection

Adds an option to setup OVS rules that will prevent
ports attached to the agent from sending any ARP responses
that contain an IP address not belonging to the port
(in fixed IPs or allowed_address_pairs).

It is disabled by default and requires the OVS version that
can match on ARP fields (>=2.1).

This prevention is specific to OVS so it will not help with
other plugins that use the reference iptables filtering. A
non-OVS-specific general approach will require something like
the ebtables integration in Ibc6d3d520c1383cf7e00f4bdeb7853a41ac4b14b.

Details:
A new table is added for ARP spoofing prevention. All ARP traffic
on the local switching table is sent to this spoofing table.
The spoofing table will allow all ARP requests because we aren't
interested in them. It will then install an ARP response allow rule
for each IP address the port is assigned. All other ARP responses are
dropped.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1274034

Change-Id: I7c079b779245a0af6bc793564fa8a560e4226afe

commit_message:
Add simple ARP spoofing protection

Adds an option to setup OVS rules that will prevent
ports attached to the agent from sending any ARP responses
that contain an IP address not belonging to the port
(in fixed IPs or allowed_address_pairs).

It is disabled by default and requires an OVS version that
can match on ARP fields. If it is too old, traffic will
still flow but it won't have ARP spoofing protection.
There is a sanity check to verify that ARP header matching
is supported.

This prevention is specific to OVS so it will not help with
other plugins that use the reference iptables filtering. A
non-OVS-specific general approach will require something like
the ebtables integration in Ibc6d3d520c1383cf7e00f4bdeb7853a41ac4b14b.

Details:
A new table is added for ARP spoofing prevention. All ARP traffic
on the local switching table is sent to this spoofing table.
The spoofing table will allow all ARP requests because we aren't
interested in them. It will then install an ARP response allow rule
for each IP address the port is assigned. All other ARP responses are
dropped.

DocImpact
SecurityImpact
Partial-Bug: #1274034

Change-Id: I7c079b779245a0af6bc793564fa8a560e4226afe

just to clarify, is the issue that if the policy.json file doesn't have a 'default' value, it breaks?"}, {'account_id': 13637, 'date': '2015-03-31 17:03:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

well..The problem with the current code is that if a specific key (for eg. get_meters) is not explicitly mentioned in the policy.json , it does not check for the default value. So , let's say I make v2/meters call and "get_meters" is not mentioned among the set of rules in the policy.json , ideally it show consider the default value (i e if default value is defined) or return false (as per the logic in oslo_policy) . However, the current code does none. The current code does absolutely nothing (i e no rbac related validation) if the rule is not specified in the policy.json. This occurs because the rbac.enforce gets all the rule keys and loops through them and checks if the rule key corresponding to the requested rest api is present in policy.json . Instead , it should just pass the control to oslo_policy because oslo_policy already has all that logic implemeted.'}, {'account_id': 13637, 'date': '2015-03-31 17:09:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

The changes made as part of this review for rbac.py removes the looping through the rule keys and forwards the control to oslo_policy so that it uses oslo_policy to implement rbac validation .With this change, if a rule key for a rest api is not defined in the policy.json , the default value will be used and if there is no default value , the oslo_policy enforce method will return a false.'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-03-31 17:33:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Divya,
  if you don't specify any corresponding policy method in the policy file you really want to preserve the old behavior (backward compatible) where the only thing that Ceilometer checks is that you are an admin or not. This is taken care in the two legacy methods where the segregation policy is used. If you introduce a default that is empty, like you do, you are not adding anything to what it is currently doing, but if you then change the value of that default to something then you break the old behavior. Project access scope in Ceilometer API is messy to say the least."}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-03-31 19:30:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Fabio, the introduction of the segregation rule actually broke backward compat, since that didn't exist prior to Juno. But we can fix that by modifying the get_limited_to method to use the context_is_admin rule if the segregation rule doesn't exist. As for the addition of a default rule... that doesn't have to break backward compat either, if we do things your way when the default rule is missing and Divya's way when the default rule is present.

@Divya, I've coded up a fix for both the segregation and default rule usage to make them backward compatible. Works in my testing. I'll email to you so you can update your patch here."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2015-03-31 19:30:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Divya,

Thanks for your patch, please see the associated discussion on the ML:

  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/060209.html

With the proposed changes, I believe we can land this for kilo-rc1.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 13637, 'date': '2015-04-01 14:59:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-04-01 15:02:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-01 16:11:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

'}, {'created': '2015-03-27 13:35:45.000000000', 'message': 'Adds support for default rule in ceilometer policy.json.

The default rule is broken in the current implementation of
ceilometer rbac, because ceilometer rbac.py does not leverage
the support provided by oslo_policy . It instead tries to
loop through all the rules in the policy.json to check if the
rule corresponding to the requested REST api matches with the
any in the policy.json. In this process, it completely ignores
the existence of the default rule.

Closes-Bug: 1435855

Change-Id: Icab626b28d14514b0f024df447a8e7f35c52257c

commit_message:
Adds support for default rule in ceilometer policy.json.

The default rule is broken in the current implementation of
ceilometer rbac, because ceilometer rbac.py does not leverage
the support provided by oslo_policy . It instead tries to
loop through all the rules in the policy.json to check if the
rule corresponding to the requested REST api matches with the
any in the policy.json. In this process, it completely ignores
the existence of the default rule.

Closes-Bug: 1435855

Change-Id: Icab626b28d14514b0f024df447a8e7f35c52257c

commit_message:
Update openstack-common reference in openstack/common/README

The README file under the openstack/common directory references to
openstack-common, but the link points to oslo-incubator (which is
correct). Update the file, so it use oslo-incubator instead of
openstack-common.

Closes-Bug: 1434370

commit_message:
Update openstack-common reference in openstack/common/README

The README file under the openstack/common directory references to
openstack-common, but the link points to oslo-incubator (which is
correct). Update the file, so it use oslo-incubator instead of
openstack-common.

Change-Id: I7bd165772e4c3043cf4f08048dd2730eee7e2b06
Closes-Bug: 1434370

commit_message:
use oslo.messaging dispatch filter

oslo.messaging has the ability to filter notifications prior to
dispatching message to endpoints. we should use it.

Change-Id: Icafa81cce25e173e109b221010402ceb02023abb

commit_message:
Add comment line to blacklisting rules

By default, udevd will abuse into log if some of the rules is
empty files. There is 2 points:
 * we adding blank comment line to every suitable udev blacklisting
   rule when _blacklist_udev_rules applies

 * we do nothing when _unblacklist_udev_rules applies, cause it is
   bootstrap node fs - we can don't care about it at all

Change-Id: I61179d9ad1384aec8ce773fe1f122912b3e05aa2
Closes-Bug: #1435847

commit_message:
Make dynamic ui return 404 instead of 500 if requirement not found

Before dynamic_ui raised KeyError and returned 500. Now it returns 404
if the package is not present in the db. That caused incorrect message
to be shown to the user

Change-Id: I9ebacaefe6373d636e0e253cd81b66fcaf11c3af
Closes-Bug: #1440043

commit_message:
Parse api errors during package and bundle uploads

Before only a generic error message would be shown in case an error
occurred during package upload.
Adds a common method to parse api v1 webob-based errors and handles
errors during package/bundle upload

Change-Id: I050dd80f80adacc347e9df9587ae8415f920ab1f

commit_message:
Action log updated for running deploy task

In case of stopping deployment or removing cluster
we update action log end_timestamp for running deploy task.
It allows to send such action logs to stats collector.

Change-Id: I795dd333beb32eedf5a5b39ee8f6190650d387b9
Closes-Bug: #1401554

commit_message:
Add retries to upload_cirros task

In order to avoid deployment failure due to possible intermittent
issues with connectivity we should perform several tries for image
upload. Also we need to fix exit code for upload_cirros.rb script.

Change-Id: I6f13f5b17ab7c0794bcf7f8cba53681de2b1daf9
Closes-bug: #1422369

commit_message:
Fix the problem with default route overwriting

Before any port configuration we check and kill dhclient due
to if it is exist it carries on updating routing table and at the
end we do not have that expected. All further l3 configuration we
do later if it is needed.

* Merge all 'option' into one array

commit_message:
Fix the problem with down interface

Add interface turning on due to resource l3_ifconfig was not ready to be
called alone. It assumed that interface is up.

Change-Id: I36065a44a33a942ac78298fc6bef9ca3e45a3e27
Closes-bug: #1436540

once ago, I have written some code to avoid use local real config files when running tox, but those code is reverted in a following patch unexpectedly, since you came across same problem, I'd rather to use those code again.

see https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/commit/59e647f82c3b89f94517a1c3b15a40d677ccec79#diff-13c55f4b0293c34d2d84139eff6ddc7d

the problem is that, at that time, there is a etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf example file, but now we have removed it. A workaround may be that we generate a temp empty file like what we do in test_bin.py, the sample ceilometer.conf only contains default values so this has equal result IIUC"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-03-27 11:17:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree that we should make sure the tests do not use established configs, but that doesn't not change the fact that the test changed here should not be using a static string when it could be using the value from config.

Wherever the config comes from, if that config changes then the test with a static string would need to be updated. commit_message:
Avoid conflict with existing gnocchi_url conf value

If for some reason there is an existing ceilometer.conf lying around
that has a gnocchi_url setting in the [alarms] section then that
value will be used when running the test. We need to use that value
when validating the match, not a hardcode host string.

Change-Id: I0e23e3c380543fb491468977294cdbe11f58fa07

Updating the developer quickstart guide

needed to be filled out for current usage.

commit_message:
Add note about policy changes for os-floating-ips and os-floating-ip-pools

Also, added these (missing) extensions: os-floating-ips, os-floating-ip-pools,
os-floating-ips-bulk, and os-floating-ip-dns.

Change-Id: I7cc256e52d44a43e114a24745ff880c81b6112ee
Closes-Bug: #1424905
Closes-Bug: #1425829

commit_message:
Updates to the EDP doc

Made general corrections, tried to make the Java job section more
readable, and added explanations for the following parameters:

* edp.spark.adapt_for_swift
* edp.substitute_data_source_for_name
* edp.substitute_data_source_for_uuid

Change-Id: Ida7ec396998ade72f3137785cab27a0b4acae357

commit_message:
Work with pymongo 3.0

pymongo 3.0 renamed mongos_enum to read_pref_mode_from_name which
was causing the unit tests to fail.

Conflicts:
	keystone/common/cache/backends/mongo.py

Change-Id: Iaa7fd7221c2e6c865633ef342e6b83304a1de655
Closes-Bug: 1441393
(cherry picked from commit 7c3fe6acaef6fc283c383fb79f06e388df6e6926)

commit_message:
Add workbook and workflow validation endpoints

Add endpoints v2/workbooks/validate and v2/workflows/validate to the
REST API for workbook and workflow validation respectively. Use POST
method to submit spec for validation.

Change-Id: I0ef7d7d115b5fb59e8bd23bcc723ed8911994552
Implements: blueprint api-validate-dsl

commit_message:
Add Bandit security lint checking via tox

The idea is to make the codebase gate on Bandit.  Bandit is
produced by the OpenStack security team to do static code
analysis for security implementation failures.  It tests
the code base for ~30 common security problems in Python
with more to come.

run with:
    tox -e bandit

Partially-Implements: blueprint gate-bandit

Change-Id: Iade9936268a539384d6067104f02f9a9001c3627

http://15.126.220.115/3874/170690/c39363d7af50fe7f66851af6fb151fd9d9bc5274/         : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2015-04-05 07:22:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Honestly I don't see a relation between new session and db-access lock. How that can interrelate? Am I missing anything?

Regarding the change itself - it makes sense even if it doesn't help with original problem"}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-04-05 14:40:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

@enikanorov: I'm very confident that this is related to the
original DB deadlock failures. I was able to reproduce the
failure locally (see steps to reproduce in this bug 
description:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1440192, note that
DVR does not need to be enabled), and this
patchset completely eliminates the problem. Secondly, if
you look at the logs for the original DB deadlock failures,
there is an ~52 second delay in delete port processing for
a DHCP port (at the end of this delay, you'll see a "No
namespaces available for this DVR port"). What's happening
in this 52 seconds? I tracked this delay down to the 
query in l2_db.get_port_binding_host, and I believe it's
the fact that this query is using a new session that
causes the delay and causes a deadlock condition for other
tests running concurrently. Here's my theory... Let's say
you have 2 tests running concurrently:
- Test 1: Uses DHCP, deletes DHCP port as part of cleanup.
- Test 2: Creates an IPv6 SLAAC subnet
When Test 1 does the DHCP port delete, it will get a
"db-access" lock (in ML2 plugin's delete_port), and shortly
after l3plugin.dvr_deletens_if_no_port gets called, which
then calls ml2_db.get_port_binding_host. This
method creates a new DB session, and tries to do a query
into the PortBinding table, but the new session is blocked
because of the "db-access" lock owned by the prior session.
(This is the start of the 52 second delay, during which
time, the "db-access" lock is never released.)
At this point, Test 2 is allowed to run. When Test 2 creates
an IPv6 SLAAC subnet (on the *same* network that Test 1 is
using, by the way), it calls
_create_subnet_from_implicit_pool, which then tries to
update all ports on all other subnets on the network via
a call to _add_auto_addrs_on_network_ports. This method
tries to do updates to the Neutron port tables, but of
course it is blocked by Test 1, which has the "db-access"
lock. The deadlock is not resolved until after a lock wait
timeout.'}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-04-05 14:41:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 14216, 'date': '2015-04-05 14:42:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Build failed. For help on isolating this failure, please contact cisco-openstack-neutron-ci@cisco.com. To re-run, post a 'recheck cisco-vpnaas' comment.

- vpnaas http://128.107.233.10:8080/job/vpnaas/1565 : FAILURE in 29s"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-04-05 15:24:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Nice Eugene! Only a suggestion inline, to keep the signature consistent with the rest of the methods that do indeed use the context for DB access.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-04-05 15:25:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Armando: Apologies, I should have added some clarifying notes.
This patch (#170690) resolves the deadlock timeouts and I believe should be considered for merging, but there are still occasional IntegrityError errors in
_add_auto_addrs_on_network_ports.
The other patch (#170968) also resolves the deadlock timeouts through the use of a db-access lock (although this lock is not necessary if #170690 is used as a dependency), and it also has issues with occasional IntegrityError errors in _add_auto_addrs_on_network_ports.
I believe that the best plan is to go ahead with this patch (#170690) for the deadlock, and use the other patch (#170968) to address the IntegrityErrors. For the IntegrityErrors, my feeling is that we should just catch the exception and ignore (with a debug log message), since the port has just been deleted while we're trying to update it. (I don't know how the port is getting deleted midstream, maybe it has to do with 'ON DELETE CASCADE' operation to complete on the port tables?)"}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-04-07 23:05:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

[{'created': '2015-04-04 23:22:16.000000000', 'message': 'DBDeadlock caused by blocked call in dvr_deletens_if_no_port

If a DHCP, load balancer, or internal Neutron port is deleted, and
the L3 plugin that is being used supports DVR, then a call to the
L3 plugin's dvr_deletens_if_no_port() method is made. This call
is made within the context of a "db-access" lock.

Within the dvr_deletens_if_no_port() method, a call is then made
to the ML2 DB get_port_binding_host() method. The
get_port_binding_host method then creates a *new* database session
with:
    session = db_api.get_session()
and then does a query to the PortBinding table. This new session
gets blocked because of the "db-access" lock held by the previous
session. If another thread then tries to do a database access, it
will cause a deadlock.

This patch creates a version of the get_port_binding_host method
that reuses the existing context session to do the database query
in order to avoid a deadlock.

Change-Id: I8aafb0a70f40f9306ccc366e5db6860c92c48cce
Closes-Bug: #1440192

commit_message:
Re-use context session in ML2 DB get_port_binding_host

This patch modifies ML2 DB get_port_binding_host method so that it
reuses the existing context session to do the database query
rather than creating a new database session.

Note that there are other methods in ML2 DB that do not re-use
the caller's session (get_port_from_device_mac() and
get_sg_ids_grouped_by_port()). These will be modified using
a separate bug (https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1441205).
Change-Id: I8aafb0a70f40f9306ccc366e5db6860c92c48cce
Closes-Bug: #1440183

commit_message:
test_resource for functional tests

Introduces new resource plugin to be able to test various
functional test cases which includes Rollback, Update In Place,
Concurrent Update and can be customised furthur based on the needs.

Co-Authored-by: Anant Patil <anant.patil@hp.com>

Change-Id: I3b8a1d2928553c87abaac81ee687e0faa85c9c5e

change croniter.cur time, then if it is not exactly match, the cur time is
no longer the current time, and the second call to get_prev() is not same
as first get_prev(), finally, a wrong value may returned.

For example, if start="0 11 31 * *", and current time is 2015-03-31T11:30:00,
then first get_prev() is 2015-03-31T11:00:00, but second one is 2015-05-01T11:00:00

commit_message:
reset croniter to avoid cur time shift

When we evaluate alarms, we check the time constraints, and will check
if it is exactly match firstly, but croniter get_prev() and get_next() will
change croniter.cur time, then if it is not exactly match, the cur time is
no longer the current time, and the second call to get_prev() is not same
as first get_prev(), finally, a wrong value may returned.

For example, if start="0 11 31 * *", and current time is 2015-03-31T11:30:00,
then first get_prev() is 2015-03-31T11:00:00, but second one is 2015-05-01T11:00:00

This patch fixes it by creating a new croniter object with current time.

Change-Id: Iaeb1f763ffc33b726d132a234c8e4e08db00a8fe
Closes-Bug: #1438674

commit_message:
Add port-security extension API cases for Neutron

Netron ml2 plugin introduces a new extension port-security from Kilo cycle,
this patch add the API test cases for it. It verifies the default value of the
attribute, for network and port. And It also verifies the confict between
setting port-security and sec-group/address-pairs.

Change-Id: I11c5a720b6e0d5e12f994187358a30c57a693ad0

commit_message:
User Guides: "Fix" common files

Only place files in common that are used in both User Guides, move the
others out to the proper guide (End User in all cases).

This leaves a few files in common for now, they might be used by other
guides in the future.

[{'created': '2015-04-07 22:38:29.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent share server creation with unsupported network types with cDOT

The segmentation approach used by the network plugin associated with a share
server was not declared to the driver. This made it impossible for a driver
to know whether a network used VLAN, GRE, VXLAN, or any other segmentation
approach, and introduced the possibility of an incorrect segmentation

commit_message:
Prevent share server creation with unsupported network types with cDOT

This patchset proposes to make NetApp Data ONTAP driver fail correctly
on unsupported network types such as VXLAN and GRE. This patchset
applies a correct filter to check for the segmentation technology
used, and throws a clean error message if the segmentation
technology is not supported by the NetApp cDOT Driver.

Closes-bug: 1438825

Change-Id: I2329322853b8f360b83118442d759f4ea3780579

commit_message:
Add missing copy_volume_to_image method to Sheepdog driver

Copy Volume to Image feature is required since Havana release.
The Sheepdog driver has not implemented it.

Change-Id: I940095be7ed3721cc8f1bafde821fbb420d305d0
Closes-Bug: #1426431

commit_message:
Manage compute node that exposes no pci devices

Booting a VM with a pci device causes an exception when the host doesnt
have any assignable pci devices.
If a host doesnt expose any pci devices to nova, its pci_stats are set
to None. This causes an exception when the PciPassthroughFilter checks
if the host can support the pci requests.

Closes-Bug: #1435981
Change-Id: Ia9fbec9c7a3afa9b7ea73c43b21db0909a195a36

commit_message:
Further mock adjustments to deal with intermittent failure

When the py-mysql tox target is run after the py27 tox target it can
sometimes fail because a MagicMock was not properly initialized.
This change more completely fleshes out the mock so that a TypeError
does not occur when a debugging log message is caused. The
specifics of why the logging only happens sometimes are not
understood.

Change-Id: I99f80d794b757a0ac05f7a9b53974ba9913e6e68
Closes-Bug: #1438300

commit_message:
FWaaS: Reorganize unit test tree

Similar to what is happening in Neutron, this commit renames and moves unit
test files so that they match the directory structure of the code tree.
Since the FWaaS repo's test files have imports from Neutron, there are import
changes as well, to the imports to match the Neutron test file organization.
A check script is added to monitor the test file naming and locations (to
ensure consistency).

Note: In the future the Neutron check_unit_test_structure.sh should be made
configurable, and duplicate files removed from *aaS repos.

Change-Id: I4cf1093eac88f62bbe1303233bfd37058db3821a
Closes-Bug: #1441501

commit_message:
pymongo 3.0 breaks ci gate

we pass safe parameter to pymongo.MongoClient but this field is
removed in 3.0. the default value is safe=True as of pymongo>=2.4[1].
this patch also cleans up residual ensure_index usage in tests which
were leftover from when ttl was not native to mongodb[2]

[1] http://emptysqua.re/blog/pymongos-new-default-safe-writes/
[2] I3d91fb08eb51ba6cfd5256abbeca43ed98321412

Closes-Bug: #1441393
Change-Id: I46f6ba28a4986c1f35b726c411d0804f3bb0cbda

commit_message:
Update openstack-common reference in openstack/common/README

The README file under the openstack/common directory references to
openstack-common, but the link points to oslo-incubator (which is
correct). Update the file, so it use oslo-incubator instead of
openstack-common.

Change-Id: I0abba6f0f882309ec281124ad956967711e02971
Closes-Bug: 1434370

Note that I was not suggesting to make the whole change in this patch. However, if we think it makes sense to make this the default behavior, we should start doing that in this patch. 

That is, add a deprecation warning (or note this in the change log) so that people will know the behavior will change.

@Stuart, Many patches have been blocked lately because "there are scripts using the client as is". TBH, I think we should stop using that as a blocker for changing behaviors we think should be changed. If a good deprecation path is provided, scripts will be able to be updated properly and without breaking.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-03-24 10:51:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Flavio

I understand where you're coming from, but my preference is, as much as possible, to provide a stable, predictable experience for users.

Folks might have entire in-house test suites or scripts for publishing images that check that the uploaded image size is what is expected. I believe that they should fairly expect not to have to rewrite them.

(Similarly, I don't think that a patch to change 'swift stat' to give human readable size output by default would get approved.)"}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-03-24 11:37:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Agree with Stuart that we shouldn't change the default behavior and that human-readable should be explicitly called by the user to make such output. In that case the backward compatibility will be preserved."}, {'account_id': 13861, 'date': '2015-03-25 08:56:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Flavio,

I too agree with @stuart and @Kamil, human-readable should be provided as additional rather than default for backward compatibility.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-03-25 13:12:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Again, I'm not proposing to remove the current behavior in this patch. What I'm trying to do is to find a consensus on what we want to do in the long run.

Do we want to make human-readable the default behavior in the future? If yes (my preference) then we should keep the patch as is and add a warning that says the current behavior will change. If not, then there's nothing to do.

In my first comment, I believe I was very clear on what my question was. I understand Stuart's preference is to keep it as is because migrating scripts will apparently be hard (which I don't believe). However, it'd be nice to have other fokls opinions too. I'm just trying to build a better experience for the user consuming the library. I don't really care that much in this particular case. Nonetheless, if we're adding a new CLI parameter, it probably means there's a use case for it."}, {'account_id': 13861, 'date': '2015-03-25 14:57:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
glance image-show now have --human-readable option

Added option '--human-readable' to image-show cli which allows users
to display image size in human-readable format.

Change-Id: Ic3452ce4560d3cf90fa7f59f98e5ff42e804f8c9
Closes-Bug: #1434381

commit_message:
Use the package name when looking up version

We need to give PBR the full package name when it looks up the version
from a pip installed package. keystoneclient_kerberos is the module
name, not the package name.

Change-Id: I638d0975d77db3767c3675dceb05466388abebc9
Closes-Bug: #1441918

commit_message:
WIP: fix kafka unit test code

The kafka unit test code behavior something odd:

* there is a bug in ut which assigns less arguments then expected
* KafkaBrokerPublisher always tries to connect to localhost when
  __init__, but there may exist if developer has kafka service running
  locally, then the _send() will succeed

This patch mainly does:

1. pass proper number of arguments to publish_samples
2. mock _get_client() before KafkaBrokerPublisher is initialized
3. mock _send() to ensure things happen as we expect, not so
   necessary with bullet 2 but still meanful

Change-Id: Ibe1e275bce6c04815ea204ce5a5ebd83ce7b9980
Closes-Bug: #1441175

commit_message:
Update os-client-config min version

The os-client-config library changed its default dogpile backend
from memory to null after 0.6.0 was released. Caching is pretty
much broken in shade, at the moment, so let's make 0.7.0 the
minimum version.

Change-Id: I640b0f50b195bd63db185a64d2a5223781f424d1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-13 02:24:24.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent max_count > 1 and specified ip address as input

Previously, if one did:
   nova boot --num-instances 2 --nic net-id=<net_id>,v4-fixed-ip=10.0.0.17
this would result in all of the instances failing to boot because neither
nova-network or neutron allows multiple instances to have the same ip_address.
This patch fixes this from occuring by checking for this and raising an error
to the caller from nova-api.

Change-Id: I7e44d58e66aeb10fb15c3553072f988f65ab823b

commit_message:
Prevent max_count > 1 and specified ip address as input

Previously, if one did:
   nova boot --num-instances 2 --nic net-id=<net_id>,v4-fixed-ip=10.0.0.17
this would result in all of the instances failing to boot because neither
nova-network or neutron allows multiple instances to have the same ip_address.
This patch fixes this from occuring by checking for this and raising an error
to the caller from nova-api.

Change-Id: I7e44d58e66aeb10fb15c3553072f988f65ab823b
Closes-bug: 1318754
(cherry picked from commit 1181d5e65f5488bdd147ef28ffe3e14c09862cec)
Co-Authored-By: yanheven <yanheven@gmail.com>

commit_message:
NetApp cDOT driver uses deprecated APIs for NFS exports

The nfs-exportfs-* APIs that the NetApp cDOT driver currently uses
for NFS export management are 7-mode APIs which were left in for
backwards compatibility. It's not the recommended/supported way
to do NFS export management. We need to modify the driver to use
the supported set of export-policy-* and export-rule-* APIs.

Closes-Bug: #1370761
Closes-Bug: #1437509
Change-Id: I91347d27ba69d4a20fe73ce7e75f58c9818ea6d8

It's not safe to assume that a tenant id is a UUID. Some of our legacy tenants have a simple integer as their id.

This also looks like a (possibly) user-impacting change to an existing API? The kind of thing that slips through during a release cycle and makes operators angry afterwards :)

If the API contract is changing, maybe it would be better to indicate in the response whether the request resulted in a deletion?"}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-09-16 01:08:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

@Kieran - thanks! I didn't realise there was an old format for tenant id. Are there any other valid tenant id formats? I was just looking for some simple input validation so say when someone passes a tenant name rather than tenant id it is not quietly ignored.

Looks like knowing if any entries are deleted is a non trivial change so probably not appropriate for Juno. But will consider a change for Kilo."}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-09-16 01:09:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 5733, 'date': '2014-09-16 01:18:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think the format of a tenant id is undefined. I suspect it could be anything, particularly if Keystone is backed by LDAP. Someone from Keystone would be able to confirm.

commit_message:
Fixes poor input validation of quota set delete method

Improves the poor input validation of the quota set delete method
so the tenant id is at least checked to see if it looks like a
uuid. Avoids silently failing to delete a quota set when passing
something which is obviously not a tenant id.

Change-Id: I4baf9e6b663afb4dfa78dcad63f39e935c227e3d
Closes-Bug: 1367132

commit_message:
Use inspect.getcallargs as we dropped py26 support

Since Nova officially no longer supports python2.6, we should
switch to the getcallargs from inspect module and remove
the unnecessary code and test.

Change-Id: I43cde0c56d93f36984da03400954910d3f7cdbbb

commit_message:
Update dev-quickstart doc to match new devstack model

Magnum has been converted to new devstack plugin model, so we need
to update the dev-quickstart doc.

This patch also fix a content repeat issue in devstack plugin script.

Change-Id: Ibcb93a7e83a5c7f3a3f3727b957b1c45beeed5ae
Closes-Bug: #1441514

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-05 00:48:04.000000000', 'message': 'Update keystone middleware in glance for Kilo

Update keystone authentication middleware in glance for Kilo
as follows:

1) Add global keystone_auth_plugin variable, defaults to
   "password" value.

2) Add glance_service_project_name variable because keystone
   v3 changes terminology from tenant to project. Retain
   glance_service_tenant_name variable for backwards
   compatibility.

3) Add glance_service_project_domainid and
   glance_service_user_domainid variables to enable keystone
   v3 domain features, default to "default" value.

4) Modify [keystone_authtoken] section in glance configuration
   files:

   add: auth_plugin
   add: project_domain_id
   add: user_domain_id
   change: identity_uri -> auth_url
   change: auth_uri (remove version)
   change: admin_tenant_name -> project_name
   change: admin_user -> username
   change: admin_password -> password

Partially implements: blueprint master-kilofication

Change-Id: If2427f7e9dc124dc98cf140941623688bde623ed

commit_message:
Update keystone middleware in glance for Kilo

Update keystone authentication middleware in glance to
support the v3 API in Kilo.

Partially implements: blueprint master-kilofication

Change-Id: If2427f7e9dc124dc98cf140941623688bde623ed

commit_message:
Security tests for Order resources

These tests will attempt CRUD operations on Order resources, both
with and without (dummy) project ids, and always without valid tokens.
They should all return HTTP 401s.

Change-Id: Ia268016dae350195cadfa5cf289df3f279b081e0

commit_message:
perform install_infra sooner in stack.sh

The install_infra() call needs to be done earlier since
pip_install_gr() depends on it. Also the fact that python module names
are supposed to be lower case but some use camel case is a problem
(for example with XenAPI).

Change-Id: I7012d77134fa0d9c746d87e837934e7dcb337e5c
Closes-Bug: #1441820

commit_message:
Make "RAW" in image table translatable.

Most of the format values in the images tables are acronyms
and do not need to be translated. The "RAW" value is a word and
should be translated. It really don't need to be all caps either.

Change-Id: I3465d896760b24e19dad200ab550ca95e590291c
Closes-Bug: 1441352

commit_message:
Fixup post-merge comments on cleaning document

Includes: Correctly documenting how to see the clean_step that was being
executed, and link back to the Ironic state machine for more information
on when cleaning runs.

Change-Id: Idea77144d9aad9153b8389c41765e57bb4a52978

commit_message:
Detect apache version

We try to detect apache's version.
Some distributions do not allow launching apache commands (even for detection)
if not root, so we gracefully fall back on 2.4 version configuration file
We alse add an --apache-version option to force the version in case
detection would be wrong.

Closes Bug: #1438773

Change-Id: I7d28c319601cf3919068be4ac52dd10f58a82557
